{
  "doc_id": "47486",
  "text": "TNF-α and IL-6 are produced by various cell types, including monocytes/macrophages, T cells, fibroblasts, and endothelial cells. TNF-α and IL-6 are also secreted by adipocytes and are therefore referred to as adipokines [CITATION_1] . In particular, TNF-α is a key factor in the development of NAFLD because it can induce inflammation and insulin resistance by activating proinflammatory pathways, such as the NF-κB and c-jun N-terminal kinase pathways [CITATION_2] . An elevated TNF-α level has also been demonstrated in several studies of fatty liver disease [CITATION_3] . The role of IL-6 in liver pathology is complex, although it has been associated with protection from steatosis via gp130 signalling and activation of the Jak/ Stat pathway in animal models, similar to leptin [CITATION_4] . Nevertheless, IL-6 is considered a predictive marker of insulin resistance via the induction of SOCS3 expression [CITATION_5] , and serum IL-6 levels are elevated in patients with NAFLD [CITATION_6] . As such, both TNF-α and IL-6 may be associated with hepatic lipogenesis, obesity and insulin resistance, supporting a central role for these inflammatory factors in NAFLD. To determine the effects of these representative proinflammatory factors on miRNA expression, we used them to treat HepG2 cells. Similar to the results obtained from the sequencing results, both TNF-α and IL-6 upregulated the expression of the six chosen miRNAs. We interpret this result as indicating that proinflammatory factors are key mediators of the changes in miRNA expression in NAFLD.",
